  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) laws emerged in the 1970s\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States was a pioneering legislation\n- Focus on requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. International Cooperation\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed global standards and recommendations for AML efforts\n- Promoted international collaboration and information sharing\n\n3. Key Legislative Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded reporting requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence and customer identification procedures\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Legislation addressing digital currencies and cryptocurrency\n- Requirements for online transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced tracking of complex financial networks\n\n5. Expanded Scope\n- Broadened definition of money laundering\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- Stricter regulations for high-risk industries\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Greater emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced corporate accountability\n- More sophisticated risk assessment mechanisms\n\n7. Global Standardization\n- Continuous updating of international AML frameworks\n- Harmonization of regulatory approaches across jurisdictions\n\nThese developments reflect ongoing efforts to address increasingly complex financial crimes.",
